Boil a full #kettle{}.

Trim the @carrot{1} (no need to peel), then slice into 1cm thick rounds.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} with a #grater{} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the carrot and fry until starting to soften, ~{2-3%minutes}.
Stir occasionally.

While the carrot cooks, pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with
@salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @jasmine rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12-13%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{}
and leave to the side until ready to serve.

Once the carrot has softened, stir in the garlic, @Thai style spice mix{1}
and @massaman curry paste{75%g}. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce. Add the
@vegetable stock paste{10%g}. Stir until well combined.

Bring to the boil.

Stir the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} into the sauce and bring back to
the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the chicken is cooked and the
sauce has thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging. The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, zest and cut the @lime{1/2} into wedges.

For the last ~{4-5%minutes} of cooking, add the @cavolo nero{100%g}(chopped) to
the pan and cook until wilted and piping hot.

> TIP: Discard any tough stalks from the cavolo nero before cooking.

When the curry is ready, remove from the heat. Stir in the @soy sauce{} and a
squeeze of lime juice, along with a splash of water if you feel it needs it.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and more lime juice if needed.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

Serve the zesty rice in #bowls{} with the chicken curry on top and a lime
wedge alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!